{"title":"OUTFOX: LLM-Generated Essay Detection Through In-Context Learning with Adversarially Generated Examples","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"LLM-generated text detectors are brittle: simple paraphrasing and adaptive attackers can sharply reduce accuracy, and prior work rarely models an attacker that conditions on a detector’s outputs. Detectors also typically require training/fine-tuning, limiting responsiveness to new attacks.","method":"OUTFOX is a training-free, in-context learning framework where a detector and an attacker co-adapt using each other’s outputs. The detector (ChatGPT) retrieves top-k semantically similar problem statements via TF-IDF and constructs in-context examples mixing human-written, non-attacked LLM, and adversarially attacked essays, labeling attacker texts as LM to teach robustness. It predicts labels with a fixed prompt and zero randomness. This design improves robustness to adaptive attacks, yielding up to +41.3 F1 on attacked texts while maintaining strong non-attacked performance (state-of-the-art up to 96.9 F1)."},{"problem":"Existing attack evaluations mostly rely on paraphrasing, which may not adequately capture adaptive, stronger adversaries that directly target detector weaknesses.","method":"OUTFOX introduces an adaptive, generation-based attacker that uses the detector’s predicted labels on retrieved, similar LLM essays as in-context examples. Given a problem statement, it conditions on tuples (problem, detector label, essay) and is instructed to write an essay ‘detected as Human’ with matched word count, using ChatGPT at higher temperature. This produces essays more semantically similar to human writing than non-attacked LLM outputs and degrades detectors far more than paraphrasing (e.g., up to −57.0 F1 on the proposed detector; stronger than DIPPER)."},{"problem":"There is a lack of large-scale, realistic datasets of native-student essays paired with problem statements and matched LLM outputs to study detection and adaptive attacks.","method":"The authors construct a dataset from the Feedback Prize corpus by generating pseudo problem statements and corresponding essays from multiple LMs (ChatGPT, GPT-3.5, FLAN-T5-XXL), yielding 15,400 triplets (problem, human essay, LLM essay) per LM with a 14400/500/500 split. They also provide attacked essays for the test set per attacker and release code/data to support reproducible detection and attack research."}]}
